{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533757","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533757"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:40:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:40:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14871"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14871"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.18,0.05,0.09,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109337"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7562"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91701"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"3758"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40845"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109337"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with fever and lethargy. She is receiving chemotherapy for breast cancer and had her most recent cycle five days ago. She has no other medical history and takes no regular medications apart from her chemotherapy. She appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 110/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. She has no obvious source of infection on examination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 105 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 0.8 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils 0.3 x 10^9/L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 120 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate empiric antibiotic therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flucloxacillin","Ceftriaxone plus metronidazole","Vancomycin","Amoxicillin-clavulanate","Piperacillin-tazobactam"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with febrile neutropenia, defined as a single oral temperature of \u226538.3\u00b0C or temperature \u226538.0\u00b0C sustained over one hour, in a patient with a neutrophil count \u0026lt;0.5 x 10^9/L. This is a medical emergency requiring prompt recognition and treatment to prevent sepsis-related mortality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPiperacillin-tazobactam\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line empiric antibiotic therapy for febrile neutropenia. It provides broad-spectrum coverage against both gram-positive and gram-negative organisms, including \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E. It should be administered within 60 minutes of presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E provides inadequate coverage for febrile neutropenia. It lacks activity against \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas\u003C/em\u003E species and many other gram-negative organisms commonly encountered in neutropenic sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeftriaxone plus metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for intra-abdominal sepsis but does not provide adequate \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas\u003C/em\u003E coverage for febrile neutropenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate as empiric therapy as it only covers gram-positive organisms. It may be added to the regimen if there are specific risk factors such as suspected central line infection or MRSA colonisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E is too narrow in spectrum, covering only susceptible staphylococci and streptococci. It would be inappropriate as empiric therapy in febrile neutropenia where broad-spectrum coverage is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating empiric antibiotics, patients should be risk-stratified based on factors including depth and expected duration of neutropenia, comorbidities, and clinical stability to determine the need for hospitalisation and ongoing management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Empiric broad-spectrum antibiotics should be commenced within 60 minutes in febrile neutropenia.","Piperacillin-tazobactam is first-line empiric therapy for febrile neutropenia."],"references":["Antibiotic. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; accessed {04 Nov 2024}. https://www.tg.org.au","Lingaratnam S, Slavin MA, Koczwara B, et al. Introduction to the Australian consensus guidelines for the management of neutropenic fever in adult cancer patients, 2010/2011. Australian Consensus Guidelines 2011 Steering Committee. Intern Med J. 2011;41(1b):75-81. doi:10.1111/j.1445-5994.2010.02338.x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91701"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14871"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91701"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-20T13:57:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-20T13:58:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7562"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"qu